snippet.textDisplay:
"3:58 the Chinese word for meat, "rou" literally means pork; all other types of meat have to be specified"

Please give me a citation on this
As a Chinese, I have never heard of the character used specifically for pork, but as a broad term of any type of animal's meat.
We do separate fish (鱼) and meat (肉), and refer the later for muscle or fat of domesticated meat sources such as cattle or chicken.
For pig, we have various characters such as 豚 (tún); 彘 (zhì); or 豕 (shǐ) in ancient Chinese. 猪 (zhū) is a younger invention.

But as far as I'm concerned, no ancient Chinese or modern ones use 肉 to represent pork

snippet.textDisplay: China is, and has always been, by far the world leader in the plant-based meat industry. The history of consuming plant-based meat dates back at least a thousand years, when certain tofu products were documented as "small mutton". The demand of artificial meat was originally related to the Buddhist vegetarian diet, but later deeply rooted in cuisines across China. Due to this long history, the Chinese plant-based meat "industry" is heavily decentralised and have therefore not produce a single leading company. The recent trend of plant-based meat in the west has already triggered Chinese competitions in this industry that they knew very well of. It wouldn't be a surprise if some Chinese plant-based meat companies become household names in the near future.

The Chinese government is fully aware there power and the people's faith in the authoritarian regime rests on one fact simple fact: People being content. This means they have shelter, food, a job, and an outlook that things are getting better. Once the people are no longer content, they will fall back to using fear but you can only dip into that bucket so much.

I am of the opinion global democracy is inevitable, though its creep is slow. China's manufacturing boom being the factory of the world will one day move to Africa and parts of central and south America and that's when the trouble will start for the authoritarian regime. They are attempting to counter this by investing across the world and punishing businesses that defy them financially. That won't work when the foreign money stops rolling in. I have nothing but respect for the Chinese people and their culture is rich and ancient. Their food is pretty damn tasty too. That said state sponsored censorship and having no influence on who leads my country is against everything I believe as an American. I expect some snarky comment about this but the US, Australia, Japan, South Korea and the countries of western Europe are the best examples of governments working for the people and created by the people the world has seen thus far. I will deal with some corruption and scandals over having my internet blocked from looking at Winnie the Pooh because of a joke.
